CORONAVIRUS DISEASE 2019 UPDATE (433): ANIMAL, DENMARK (NORTH JUTLAND, MID JUTLAND) FARMED MINK, SPREAD, CONTROL
****************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Fri 9 Oct 2020 21:03 CEST
Source: TV-2 North (Denmark) [in Danish, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.tv2nord.dk/jammerbugt/konflikten-fortsaetter-minkavlere-sagsoeger-myndighederne


Mink breeders are so dissatisfied with the authorities' handling of the killing of their mink that they are now suing the state. The purpose is both to ensure better financial compensation and to ensure a fair process for the killing of the minks.

[One of the mink breeders] was directed to kill his herd due to the government's plan to reduce infection among the hard-hit North Jutland farms. He feels so badly treated by authorities and politicians that he is therefore now, together with the North Jutland Mink Breeders' Association and a number of North Jutland mink breeders, suing the state. "We feel insulted. We feel trampled on, and all our rights are set aside", [he] says.

The purpose of the lawsuit is to point out the mistakes committed by the authorities, according to the mink breeders. They have now contacted [a lawyer]. She will be in charge of advising the mink breeders legally. Although she only became involved in the case on Friday [9 Oct 2020], she already has a clear idea of where the problem lies, according to the mink owners. "No decision has been made in advance. No information has been received on when they will arrive. You will not receive a letter of legal certainty stating your rights. Fifty men come in spacesuits and take their life's work from them", says [the lawyer].

The lawsuit has both a long-term and short-term purpose. In the short term, they want to stop the ongoing killing of mink until they have ensured that the Danish Veterinary and Food Administration complies with all relevant rules in the area. "We must have a fair compensation that covers our costs, and it must be equal for everyone -- regardless of whether [your farm is] infected or not. If we do not succeed, I cannot foresee the consequences, says [the lawyer].

Minister of Food, Agriculture and Fisheries Mogens Jensen did not want to comment on the mink breeders' lawsuit.

[byline: Soren Nielsen and Thomas Kring]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
